" ============================================================================
" .codemeowrc — THE default keymap of the codemeow extension
" ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
" Like meow in Emacs, the extension binds no keys in code: this file defines
" every default — the NORMAL/MOTION layout and the whole SPC keypad table —
" and ships bundled inside the extension. A ~/.codemeowrc in your home
" directory (Linux/macOS: ~/.codemeowrc, Windows: C:\Users\<you>\.codemeowrc)
" overrides it entry by entry — only the lines you change matter; a deleted
" line falls back to the bundled default (bind `ignore` to disable a key).
" Open it with SPC c m — the first press creates ~/.codemeowrc as a full
" copy of this file; reload after editing with SPC c M ("Reload .codemeowrc").
"
" Syntax (see the README for the full guide):
"   nmap <key> <action>(command.id)     NORMAL-mode key -> editor command
"   nmap <key> <meow-command>           NORMAL-mode key -> named meow command
"   nmap <key> <meow keys>              NORMAL-mode key -> replayed meow keys
"   nnoremap ...                        like nmap, but the RHS resolves through
"                                       these bundled defaults, skipping user maps
"   mmap / mnoremap <key> <target>      the same, for MOTION mode (the keymap
"                                       of the workbench trees; read-only
"                                       editors stay NORMAL)
"   map <leader><seq> <target>          keypad (SPC) entry
"   desc <leader><seq> <text>           which-key label for an entry or a group
"   set timeoutlen=300                  which-key hint delay in ms
"   set nowhich-key                     turn the which-key hint off
"
" Ported from the companion ideameow .ideameowrc (itself a port of the
" .ideavimrc leader scheme). Not portable (and why) is listed at the bottom.
" The meow layout itself needs NO porting — the extension implements it
" natively; the layout section right below IS the keymap (like
" meow-normal-define-key in Emacs), so any key can be rebound. Within this
" file, a later line for the same key wins.
" ============================================================================

set which-key
set timeoutlen=300

" ============================================================================
" The meow layout — QWERTY by default, every key rebindable
" ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
" These lines ARE the default layout (there is no key table in the extension's
" code). Rebind any key to another meow command, to an <action>(...), or to
" replayed keys; bind a key to `ignore` to disable it. In a home ~/.codemeowrc
" only overrides are needed — a key without a home line keeps its binding
" from this bundled file. mmap does the same for MOTION mode.
" SPC is the keypad key and cannot be remapped; ESC and modifier
" chords never reach the modal engine (put those on VS Code's keybindings).
" ============================================================================

" expand / counts
nmap 0 meow-expand-0
nmap 1 meow-expand-1
nmap 2 meow-expand-2
nmap 3 meow-expand-3
nmap 4 meow-expand-4
nmap 5 meow-expand-5
nmap 6 meow-expand-6
nmap 7 meow-expand-7
nmap 8 meow-expand-8
nmap 9 meow-expand-9
nmap - meow-negative-argument

" selections / things
nmap ; meow-reverse
nmap , meow-inner-of-thing
nmap . meow-bounds-of-thing
nmap [ meow-beginning-of-thing
nmap ] meow-end-of-thing
nmap < meow-beginning-of-thing
nmap > meow-end-of-thing

" the letter keys
nmap a meow-append
nmap A meow-open-below
nmap b meow-back-word
nmap B meow-back-symbol
nmap c meow-change
nmap d meow-delete
nmap D meow-backward-delete
nmap e meow-next-word
nmap E meow-next-symbol
nmap f meow-find
nmap g meow-cancel-selection
nmap G meow-grab
nmap h meow-left
nmap H meow-left-expand
nmap i meow-insert
nmap I meow-open-above
nmap j meow-next
nmap J meow-next-expand
nmap k meow-prev
nmap K meow-prev-expand
nmap l meow-right
nmap L meow-right-expand
nmap m meow-join
nmap n meow-search
nmap o meow-block
nmap O meow-to-block
nmap p meow-yank
nmap q meow-quit
nmap Q meow-goto-line
nmap r meow-replace
nmap R meow-swap-grab
nmap s meow-kill
nmap t meow-till
nmap u meow-undo
nmap U meow-undo-in-selection
nmap v meow-visit
nmap w meow-mark-word
nmap W meow-mark-symbol
nmap x meow-line
nmap X meow-goto-line
nmap y meow-save
nmap Y meow-sync-grab
nmap z meow-pop-selection
nmap ' repeat

" MOTION mode — meow's reduced state for special contexts, exactly like
" special buffers in Emacs. Read-only editors do NOT use it (they stay
" NORMAL, like Emacs read-only buffers, with the modify commands inert);
" it IS the keymap of the workbench trees — the Explorer, outline, search
" results, problems, ... — where j/k/h/l move like the arrow keys (h
" collapses or goes to the parent, l expands or enters), q hides the side
" bar, and every unmapped key keeps its native meaning: Enter opens, any
" other letter still starts the tree's type-to-find. Add your own the same
" way, e.g.
"   mmap o <action>(filesExplorer.openFilePreserveFocus)          open, stay in the tree
"   mmap r <action>(workbench.files.action.refreshFilesExplorer)  NERDTree-style refresh
" and `mmap <key> ignore` gives a key back to the tree (native
" type-to-find) — on trees ignore means don't intercept, not swallow.
mmap j meow-next
mmap k meow-prev
mmap h meow-left
mmap l meow-right
mmap q <action>(workbench.action.toggleSidebarVisibility)

" ============================================================================
" The keypad (SPC) table — every entry an rc line, like the layout above
" ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
" In Emacs, SPC x / c / m reach the C-x / C-c / M- keymaps; here the same
" sequences dispatch VS Code commands, mirroring the companion .ideavimrc /
" .ideameowrc leader scheme. SPC 1-9 (digit argument), SPC ? (cheatsheet) and
" SPC / (describe key) are reserved by the keypad itself and cannot be
" remapped. Finding a command's id for <action>(...): SPC i d lists every
" command id (type to filter, Enter copies it to the clipboard), or
" Preferences > Keyboard Shortcuts, right-click an entry, "Copy Command ID".
" ============================================================================

map <leader>b <action>(workbench.action.showAllEditorsByMostRecentlyUsed)
map <leader><Space> <action>(workbench.action.quickOpenPreviousRecentlyUsedEditorInGroup)

" SPC x = C-x: files / buffers / windows
map <leader>xf <action>(workbench.action.quickOpen)
map <leader>xs <action>(workbench.action.files.saveAll)
map <leader>xb <action>(workbench.action.showAllEditorsByMostRecentlyUsed)
map <leader>xk <action>(workbench.action.closeActiveEditor)
map <leader>xd <action>(workbench.view.explorer)
map <leader>xg <action>(workbench.view.scm)
map <leader>xo <action>(workbench.action.focusNextGroup)
map <leader>xu <action>(timeline.focus)
map <leader>xv <action>(workbench.view.scm)
map <leader>xc <action>(workbench.action.closeFolder)
map <leader>x0 <action>(workbench.action.joinTwoGroups)
map <leader>x1 <action>(workbench.action.editorLayoutSingle)
map <leader>x2 <action>(workbench.action.splitEditorDown)
map <leader>x3 <action>(workbench.action.splitEditor)

" SPC x p = C-x p: project.el
map <leader>xpf <action>(workbench.action.quickOpen)
map <leader>xpb <action>(workbench.action.showAllEditorsByMostRecentlyUsed)
map <leader>xpg <action>(workbench.action.findInFiles)
map <leader>xpr <action>(workbench.action.replaceInFiles)
map <leader>xpc <action>(workbench.action.tasks.build)

" SPC c = C-c: personal commands
map <leader>cf <action>(workbench.action.quickOpen)
map <leader>cs <action>(workbench.action.files.saveAll)
map <leader>ck <action>(workbench.action.closeActiveEditor)
map <leader>cb <action>(workbench.action.showAllEditorsByMostRecentlyUsed)
map <leader>cr <action>(workbench.action.findInFiles)
map <leader>ce <action>(editor.action.smartSelect.expand)
map <leader>ca <action>(workbench.actions.view.problems)
map <leader>cc <action>(workbench.action.files.newUntitledFile)
map <leader>cl <action>(copyRelativeFilePath)
map <leader>cg <action>(workbench.view.scm)

" SPC c m / M: edit / reload ~/.codemeowrc
map <leader>cm <action>(codemeow.editRc)
map <leader>cM <action>(codemeow.reloadRc)

" SPC c j: avy jumps — implemented natively by the extension, no Code Ace
" Jumper needed
map <leader>cjw avy-goto-char-timer
map <leader>cjc avy-goto-char-timer
map <leader>cjl avy-goto-line

" SPC m = M-: meta
map <leader>mx <action>(workbench.action.showCommands)
map <leader>mo avy-goto-char-timer
map <leader>mr <action>(editor.action.smartSelect.expand)
map <leader>mR <action>(editor.action.smartSelect.shrink)
map <leader>my <action>(editor.action.clipboardPasteAction)
map <leader>m. <action>(editor.action.revealDefinition)
map <leader>mg <action>(workbench.action.gotoLine)
map <leader>msr <action>(workbench.action.findInFiles)
map <leader>msl <action>(actions.find)
map <leader>mss <action>(actions.find)
map <leader>msL <action>(workbench.action.findInFiles)
map <leader>mso <action>(workbench.action.gotoSymbol)

" SPC w: the window map (Emacs C-c w)
map <leader>wv <action>(workbench.action.splitEditor)
map <leader>ws <action>(workbench.action.splitEditorDown)
map <leader>wd <action>(workbench.action.joinTwoGroups)
map <leader>wD <action>(workbench.action.editorLayoutSingle)
map <leader>wm <action>(workbench.action.editorLayoutSingle)
map <leader>ww <action>(workbench.action.focusNextGroup)
map <leader>wW <action>(workbench.action.moveEditorToNextGroup)
" h/j/k/l: windmove, ported from init.el — directional focus over editor
" groups AND the two panes of a side-by-side diff (which plain group focus
" never crosses). The extension also binds plain Shift+arrows to these,
" i.e. (windmove-default-keybindings) — that lives in the manifest
" keybindings (rebind in Preferences > Keyboard Shortcuts > Windmove *),
" not in this rc, because modifier chords never reach the modal engine.
map <leader>wh <action>(codemeow.windmoveLeft)
map <leader>wj <action>(codemeow.windmoveDown)
map <leader>wk <action>(codemeow.windmoveUp)
map <leader>wl <action>(codemeow.windmoveRight)
map <leader>wi <action>(editor.action.fontZoomIn)
map <leader>w= <action>(editor.action.fontZoomIn)
map <leader>wo <action>(editor.action.fontZoomOut)
map <leader>w- <action>(editor.action.fontZoomOut)
map <leader>wu <action>(editor.action.fontZoomReset)
map <leader>w0 <action>(editor.action.fontZoomReset)

" --- avy jumps, mirroring init.el (a native port — nothing to install) ------
" init.el: S = avy-goto-char-timer, Q = avy-goto-line. X still goes-to-line,
" so overriding Q costs nothing.
nmap S avy-goto-char-timer
nmap Q avy-goto-line

" --- split resizing (ideavimrc: - = _ +) ------------------------------------
" '-' stays meow's negative-argument (the reason ideavimrc used '-' here was
" that vim lacks negative counts — this extension doesn't). The other three
" keys are free in the meow layout:
nmap = <action>(workbench.action.increaseViewSize)
nmap _ <action>(workbench.action.decreaseViewSize)
nmap + <action>(workbench.action.evenEditorWidths)

" --- which-key labels for the keypad groups above ----------------------------
desc <leader>b buffers (MRU editors)
desc <leader>x C-x · file / buffer / window
desc <leader>xp C-x p · project
desc <leader>c C-c · commands (= M-m)
desc <leader>cj C-c j · avy jump
desc <leader>m M- · meta
desc <leader>ms M-s · search
desc <leader>w window map (Emacs C-c w)

